Mean [minimum; maximum] values of the annual concentrations ($\mu$g/m3) of proximity air pollutants were respectively: 28 [18; 72.2] for NO2, 420 [350; 1337] for CO, 7.5[5; 13.7] for SO2, 23.1 [19; 51] for PM10, 8.1 [0.01; 116.6] for VOCs and 1.8 [1.5; 6.9] for benzene. Using a binary logistic regression model, PM10 were significantly associated with usual cough (Odds-Ratio=1.33 (95% confidence interval: 1.00–1.77) for exposed compared to non-exposed) and SO2 with usual cough (1.55 (1.16–2.08)) and phlegm (1.45 (1.04–2.01)). We found a 10% and a 23% increase in usual cough for a 10$\mu$g/m3 increment in PM10 and a 1$\mu$g/m3 increment in SO2 respectively, and a 23% increase in usual phlegm for a 1$\mu$g/m3 increase in SO2. A sensitivity analysis showed similar results when considering 3-year proximity pollution. A more pronounced effect of SO2 and PM10 on usual cough and phlegm was observed in woman.
