The annual average concentration of PM2.5 and NO2 were 10.01$\mu$g/m3 and 16.62$\mu$g/m3 respectively, across the four study areas, and were below the local Standards of 20$\mu$g/m3 and 40$\mu$g/m3, for both pollutants, respectively. In the two-pollutant-adjusted models, an interquartile range (IQR) increase of 14.2$\mu$g/m3 in NO2 was associated with an increased risk of new onset of ocular-nasal symptoms (adjusted odds ratio–aOR: 1.63, 95% CI: 1.01–2.60), wheezing (aOR: 3.57, 95% CI: 1.18–10.92), more than two or more asthma symptom score (aOR: 1.71, 95% CI: 1.02–2.86), and airway inflammation defined as FeNO > 35 ppb (aOR: 3.10, 95% CI: 1.10–8.71), independent of PM2.5 exposures.
Conclusion
This study provided evidence that ambient NO2 levels below local standards and international guidelines, independent of PM2.5 exposure, increases new cases of asthma-associated outcomes after 12-months.},
